response:
Of course, this is a geometric sequence, so the ratio between any two consecutive terms is the same. This ratio is $\frac{\frac{i+1}{i+2}}{\frac{i}{i+1}}$. Clearly, this is $\frac{\left(i+1\right)^2}{i\left(i+2\right)}$</think>

<answer>
\begin{align*}
\text{The ratio is}\quad & \frac{i+1}{i+2}\cdot\frac{i+1}{i}\\
  & =\frac{\left(i+1\right)^2}{i\left(i+2\right)}
 =\frac{i^2+2i+1}{i^2+2i}
\end{align*}
For consecutive terms, $i$ grows by $1$, so the product of the first $20$ terms will be $\left(\frac{2}{3}\cdot\frac{2}{3}\right)\cdot\frac{5}{4}\cdot\frac{4}{5}\cdot\frac{7}{6}\cdot\frac{6}{7}\cdots$, which is $\frac{2}{3}\cdot\frac{22}{20}=\boxed{\frac{11}{15}}$.
</answer>

 Find the midpoint using the midpoint formula. {(x1+x2)/2, (y1+y2)/2}
 = {(2+8)/2, (3+15)/2}
 = (5, 9) </think>
answer> (5, 9) </answer>

